ings &lt;shentino&#64;gmail.com&gt; wrote:<br />&gt;<br />&gt; So it still counts as a regression if the kernel pulls the rug out from<br />&gt; under someone that was relying on undocumented or buggy behavior?<br /><br />Absolutely. There are no excuses for regressions. If the code was<br />badly written and left itself open to user space "misusing" it, it's<br />our problem. Especially if the code was badly written to begin with,<br />and user space worked around our bad code.<br /><br />We don't then "fix" code and blame user space for doing bad things.<br /><br />In particular, we don't cop out and say "hey, you didn't follow the<br />docs" (whether they existed or not) or "you didn't do what we meant<br />you to do".<br /><br />The _only_ thing that matters is that something broke.<br /><br />             Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
